	   <tr><td colspan=2>well I didn't plan on posting on this thread, but upon reading this, I changed my mind.&nbsp;&nbsp;At this point i'm not sure which way I'd go with the "who should get loot rights to the scale"  comments, but (unless I've misunderstood what your point was) I'd say you've contridicted yourself.  You say you don't like the solo artist who thinks they're (notice the correct spelling) the bomb but go on and on about how great the bard class is (which personally I like bards and have thought many times about making one).  A successful raid is one that is made up with a balanced raiding party.  No one class is more important than the others.  Given a chance, I probably would roll for that dragon scale and complete the quest if I won.  I also wouldn't lose sleep if I wasn't able to roll on it (which just happened recently on a Vox raid I attended).  There are plenty of things that I will never see in this game, one of which is my epic.   The thing that struck me most about the Vox raid last week was how it was organized (btw Thanks EH for sponsoring that on the Tribunal server).  The raid was well organized and well planned.  The whole reason the raid happened was so that the person who organized it got a piece to his epic.  It was known going into the raid that that ONE item was spoken for by the man who put the time and effort into organizing and planning the raid.  Everyone was fine with that.  If you want that peice, my suggestion would be to do the same.  Put together your own raid and make it known That that if the scale drops it is spoken for.  If ppl don't like those rules, well...they don't have to go to YOUR raid.  I thought that was an incredibly fair way to run things.<br><br>Dalcron Spellfury<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
